course: main course
time required: 40 minutes
---

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Trim the @aubergine{2} and chop each of them into 5 pieces widthways (so you have big rounds per person). Separate the @broccoli{1} into florets (little trees!). Pop the broccoli florets on a #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and toss to coat. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}, trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and halve the @lime{½}.

Heat a glug of oil in a #frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot, lay in the aubergine pieces on one of their cut sides. Season with salt and pepper and fry until each cut side is golden, ~{3-4%minutes} each side.

> TIP: Add a little more oil if you need to.

Once browned, transfer the aubergine to a baking tray and roast on the top shelf of your oven until completely tender, ~{20-25%minutes}. 5 mins into the cooking time, pop the broccoli on the middle shelf to cook until crispy and tender too, ~{15-20%minutes}. Don't wash your frying pan - you'll use it for the sauce.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a #medium saucepan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add the shallot and cook until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pour in the @water{300%ml} and the @vegetable stock powder{1}. Bring to the boil.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until you're ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Pop your frying pan back medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil (if the pan is dry). Add the @yellow Thai style paste{45%g} and fry until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml} and squeeze in the @peanut butter{1}. Add the @sugar{½}, stir together and bring to the boil. Simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove from the heat and add a squeeze of lime juice. Taste and add more salt, pepper and lime juice if you feel it needs it. Set aside. Cut any remaining lime into wedges.

A couple of minutes before everything is ready, reheat the sauce if required and add a splash of water if necessary. Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, stir through the lime zest and spoon into #bowls{}. Top with the aubergine pieces and the roasted broccoli. Drizzle over the satay sauce and sprinkle over the spring onions. Serve with any remaining lime chopped into wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!